Comment: It was really fun and educational

✅ Approved the contribution.
Comment: Cool clash
Consider adding a test case that includes all lowercase and uppercase English letters. This will catch many trivial bugs.

hello... letters upper "e" and upper "u" are not in test cases... i think this puzzle separate alphabetic letters vowels as like upper and lower case, consonants and other kind of characters... E and U are missing in the categorization :)

✅ Approved the contribution.
Comment: Easy enough to be solvable within 5 minutes and does not favor a programming language.
Good to go in my opinion !

Fairly straight forward (definitely solvable within 5 minutes). There is a typo in the Constraints "lenght" -> "length". Otherwise it looks like everything is correct.

One thing I'd say on a personal note (again my own biased opinion)... It's not clear that Y is considered a vowel until the last test case... Someone like myself if I've found the pattern will likely not look at the last test case (and since Y generally isn't a vowel) would probably get caught up (I guess it's more of a me problem)... Because I'd start testing it, and then after it passed the first 3 I'd simply submit to save as much clock as possible... Again, I guess it would just affect those who don't look/test the last case.

Good puzzle overall.

Many thanks. I corrected the typo. 
Well, for the Y being a vowel, it looks like a cultural issue. French see it as a vowel. But, yes, in english, the letter "Y" can function as both a vowel and a consonant, depending on its use in a word. It acts as a vowel in words like "gym" and "my," while it is a consonant in words like "yellow" and "yes.". The title may give a clue :-).
Titles aren't shown in Reverse mode, but at least the last visible test gives a hint…
I changed the title of the game (A..YB..Z) and changed the first test to avoid any risk of misunderstanding.
For your information, while the titles of the clash and the cases may be useful to reviewers, none of them will be shown during an actual Reverse-mode clash.
